commText: CSK are still favourites to make it to the playoffs which would mean Dhoni will probably be back here at least one more time. But wow, those were some incredible scenes as Dhoni and the entire CSK unit took a lap around the ground to thank the fans. On that note, we wrap up our coverage. This is Sagar Chawla signing off on behalf of Harish, MS Ramakrishnan and Saurabh Shankar!

Third loss for CSK at home, and the most comprehensive one as KKR's attack found the conditions to their liking, and then Rana and Rinku put on a clinic against spin. From here, CSK go to Delhi for their final league match. At the moment the B0$. Everyone wants a glimpse of Dhoni, and even Sunil Gavaskar runs up to him for an autograph. Dhoni has a racquet in hand and is hitting some tennis balls into the crowd. He now moves on to tossing some jerseys for the fans. Don't think many have left the stadium. No one knows how long Dhoni will be around for. This sure is a very emotional gesture from both parties. Rahane also has a placard in his hands with a message for the fans. Now it's the turn of policemen who are deployed at the venue to shake hands with Dhoni and get his autographs. What scenes out there! commText: B0$ The ease of this run-chase has been extraordinary from KKR! You could argue that CSK were short of a par score, but you don't see their spinners being dominated in that fashion too often at Chepauk! Speaks volumes of how good Rinku Singh and Nitish Rana were. Dhoni is saying dew made a big difference in his post-match interview which would've helped the duo. But after getting together at 33/3 with the team in trouble, they batted brilliantly as well for the highest fourth-wicket partnership at Chepauk in IPL history. The run chase started turbulently for the visitors as Deepak Chahar rocked them with a three-fer early on. His variations and some smart field placements got rid of Gurbaz, Venky Iyer and Jason Roy. They were struggling at 46/3 after the powerplay, with potentially 12 overs of spin to follow on a sluggish pitch, and things didn't look too good. But Rinku started positively and Rana also turned it around after spending some time in the middle. And they made it look so easy out there.

commText: But leaving aside the emotions, there is a game of cricket to be played. A game of cricket with a lot riding on it. KKR travel to Chepauk knowing that a win and nothing else will keep them alive in the competition. The one positive for them is they have a spin attack that could pose some serious questions if a traditional Chepauk wicket is presented. CSK on the other hand know that they need one more win to guarantee a return to Chepauk for the qualifier. They are on a winning streak of two games, which surely would have been three had it not been for the rain in Lucknow which caused a no result.  A crucial contest coming up, stick on for the pitch report and team news….

B0$ The final group game at the Chepauk stage. Maybe, just maybe the final appearance that Thala Dhoni makes at his adopted home ground. An adopted home ground that has showered him with so much love and adulation. And Dhoni in return has reciprocated that love by giving the local CSK fans so many memorable nights, so many reasons to celebrate. Four titles, an enviable home record and countless celebratory nights. Even tonight, the CSK management have some plans chalked out to appreciate the Chepauk crowd. It is sure to be an emotional night in the office…

The Chepauk suburb of Chennai was a hub of activity in the wee hours of Friday morning. Ticket seekers, of both the genuine and proxy variety, jostled outside the MA Chidambaram Stadium ahead of the city's last league game of IPL 2023. There are two Playoff matches scheduled to be played here and Chennai Super Kings are a good bet to feature in one of them. However, sales for the post-league games come under BCCI's ambit, and with no certainty as yet on which of those matches will feature MS Dhoni, Sunday's clash against the Kolkata Knight Riders has whipped up an extra shot of the frenzy, if that was even possible.   
   
As such, the on-field narrative might pale slightly in comparison to the ongoing 'will he?' soap opera around the CSK captain and his playing future. But the team itself recognises there are crucial factors still at play and was hard at work in the nets two days out from the game when it would have been reasonable to take a day off heading into the business end of a gruelling tournament. CSK need at least a win from their two remaining games to rubber-stamp their 12th appearance in the final-four, and two in two will give them two shots at the final, an enticing prospect.   
   
KKR, on the other hand, no longer have qualification destiny in their hands. It was snatched away two nights ago in a chastening defeat to Rajasthan Royals and defeat tomorrow will confirm their elimination. It's been a strange season for the two-time winners that began with them losing their captain to injury. They then lost a glut of games in a stretch and also won some while being second best for the most part. From that standpoint alone Nitish Rana & Co. will hope there is room for a couple of miracles left in them, starting at a venue that first turned Knight dreams into reality eleven years ago.
